otballer ([[Wimbledon F.C.|Wimbledon]], [[Watford F.C|Watford]]).<ref>[https://www.gloucestershirelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/steve-talboys-tributes-wimbledon-football-3161272 Tributes paid to Gloucester City legend and former Wimbledon and Watford midfielder Steve Talboys]</ref>\n*[[Jean-Luc Th\u00e9rier]], 73, French rally driver.<ref>[https://www.rallye-sport.fr/jean-luc-therier-est-mort/ Jean-Luc Th\u00e9rier est mort] {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n*[[Guido Vandone]], 89, Italian footballer ([[Torino F.C.|Torino]]).<ref>[http://www.ansa.it/sito/notizie/sport/calcio/2019/07/31/morto-a-89-anni-guido-vandone_578a4818-10ec-4cc9-8484-7cd2dbcec607.html Morto a 89 anni Guido Vandone] {{in lang|it}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Navbox deaths}}\n\n[[Category:2019 deaths|*2019-07]]\n", "name_user": "Jonny Nixon", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e29", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deaths_in_July_2019"}
{"title_page": "John Kefalas", "text_new": "{{Infobox State Representative \n| name=John Kefalas\n| image name=Colorado-Rep-John-Kefalas.jpg\n| state_senate=Colorado\n| state=Colorado\n| district=[[Colorado's 14th Senate district|14th]]\n| term_start=2013\n| term_end=January 4, 2019\n| preceded=[[Bob Bacon]]\n| succeeded=[[Joann Ginal]]\n| state_house2=Colorado\n| state2=Colorado\n| district2=52nd\n| term_start2=January 10, 2007\n| term_end2=November 6, 2012\n| preceded2=[[Bob McCluskey]]\n| succeeded2=[[Joann Ginal]]\n| birth_date={{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1954|12|26}}\n| birth_place=[[Piraeus, Greece]]\n| death_date=\n| death_place=\n| spouse=Beth\n| profession=Activist, Legislator\n| party=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|}}\n\n'''John Michael Kefalas''' (born December 26, 1954<ref name=\"votesmart\">{{cite web |url=http://www.vote-smart.org/bio.php?can_id=29946 |title=Representative John Michael Kefalas |accessdate=2007-03-14 |work=Project Vote Smart }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>) is a politician in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Colorado]]. An educator and lobbyist before first running for the legislature in 2004, Kefalas defeated a Republican incumbent to win election to the [[Colorado House of Representatives]] as a [[United States Democratic Party|Democrat]] in 2006.  Kefalas won election to the [[Colorado Senate|State Senate]] in 2012 and represented [[Colorado's 14th Senate district|Senate District 14]] until early 2019. In 2018, Kefalas ran for and won a seat on the [[Larimer County, Colorado|Larimer County]] [[County commission|Board of County Commissioners]]. He resigned his Senate seat, and a vacancy committee nominated [[Joann Ginal]] to replace him.<ref>{{cite news |last=Coltrain |first=Nick |date=2019-01-04 |title=Fort Collins legislators seek to pursue progressive goals while avoiding voter backlash |url=https://www.coloradoan.com/story/news/2019/01/04/jeni-arndt-joann-ginal-set-stage-2019-colorado-legislature-session/2483017002/ |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan  |location= |access-date=2019-01-05 }}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life, education, and career===\nBorn in [[Piraeus, Greece]],<ref name=\"votesmart\"/> Kefalas earned a bachelor's degree in [[botany]]<ref name=\"chal52\">{{cite news |first=Nate |last=Taylor |title=Changing political landscape challenges HD52 contenders |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080703/NEWS01/807030335/1002/CUSTOMERSERVICE02 |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=July 3, 2008 |accessdate=2008-08-05 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> from [[Colorado State University]] in 1978 and then joined the [[Peace Corps]] in 1979, serving as an agricultural extension worker in [[El Salvador]].<ref name=\"votesmart\"/> After returning to the United States, he earned a master's degree in teaching, with a secondary science specialization from [[Fairleigh Dickinson University]]<ref name=\"chal52\"/> in 1982 and taught in the [[Poudre School District]]. He has also worked as an employment counselor for [[Larimer County, Colorado]], and as a health outreach worker.<ref name=\"votesmart\"/>\n\n===Public service and volunteerism===\nFrom 1997 to 2004, Kefalas worked as a public policy advocate and community development coordinator for [[Catholic Charities]]<ref name=\"char\">{{cite news |first=Jill |last=Chodak |title=Community, Coopersmith's feed the needy for Christmas |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/article/20081225/UPDATES01/81225006 |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=25 December 2008 |accessdate=2008-12-27 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> until his departure amidst a controversy regarding his public support for ''[[Roe v. Wade]]'' and [[abortion]] rights during his 2004 legislative campaign.<ref name=\"catholic\">{{cite news |first=Ted |last=Olsen |title=Colorado candidate: Catholic Charities fired me over abortion support |url=http://ctlibrary.com/11912 |work=Christianity Today |date=August 1, 2004 |accessdate=2007-11-13 }}</ref> Before entering the legislature, he directed the Colorado Progressive Coalition's Tax Fairness Project.<ref name=\"sitebio\">{{cite web |url=http://johnkefalas.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=12&Itemid=64 |title=About John |accessdate=2007-03-14 |work=JohnKefalas.org |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071008212703/http://johnkefalas.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=12&Itemid=64 |archivedate = October 8, 2007 }}</ref> He has served as a member of the Fort Collins Housing Authority and the Colorado Social Legislation Committee,<ref name=\"votesmart\"/> and, in 2001, won the City of Fort Collins Human Relations Award.<ref name=\"hra\">{{cite web |url=http://fcgov.com/hra/kefalas.php |title=John Kefalas |accessdate=2007-07-13 |work=City of Fort Collins |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060219052903/http://fcgov.com/hra/kefalas.php |archivedate = February 19, 2006}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1980 to 1994, Kefalas redirected a portion of his federal income taxes to charitable organizations<ref name=\"qmark\">{{cite news |first=Erin |last=Rosa |title=Caught in the question mark| url=http://www.rmchronicle.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=63&Itemid=26 |work=Rocky Mountain Chronicle |date=November 14, 2006 |accessdate=2007-07-12 }}</ref> as a protest against United States military actions in Central America. He has paid his income taxes in full since 1994, but continued to boycott the [[federal telephone excise tax]] as recently as 2004. As a result, Kefalas has had a [[lien]] filed him and has had wages [[garnishment|garnished]]. Kefalas has paid his back taxes and considers his actions to be a conscientious protest.<ref name=\"peacecorps\"/> He has also written about his experience of \"war tax resistance\" for the newsletter of the [[National War Tax Resistance Coordinating Committee]].<ref name=\"compl\">{{cite news |first=John |last=Kefalas |title=War Tax Resistance -- Part of the Complete Package | url=http://www.nwtrcc.org/mtap01/mtap0201.htm#Persp |work=More Than a Paycheck: News from the War Tax Resistance Movement |date=February 2001 |accessdate=2007-12-29 }}</ref> In both his 2004 and 2006 legislative campaigns, Kefalas was accused of avoiding his federal tax obligation, both by his Republican opponent and by independent political committees.<ref name=\"dirty\">\n{{cite news |first=Greg |last=Campbell |title=John Kefalas alleges dirty tactics | url=http://peacecorpsonline.org/messages/messages/467/2057191.html |work=Fort Collins Weekly |date=August 30, 2006 |accessdate=2007-12-29 }}</ref><ref name=\"real\">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mGKX36EBaMU |title=The Real John Kefalas |accessdate=2007-12-29 |work=YouTube }}</ref> Kefalas has also been an outspoken opponent of the [[Iraq War]], and has engaged in non-violent civil disobedience in protest of the war.<ref name=\"peacecorps\">{{cite news |first=Matthew |last=Benson |title=Candidate Kefalas skips taxes in protest |url=http://peacecorpsonline.org/messages/messages/467/2022859.html |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=August 5, 2004 |accessdate=2007-03-14 }}</ref>\n\nKefalas is married; he and his wife Beth have two sons &mdash; Harlan, an active-duty U.S. Army soldier who has served in Iraq, Kosovo, and Afghanistan,<ref name=\"peacewar\">{{cite news |first=John |last=Kefalas |title=Kefalas: War, Peace and Family Values |url=http://www.fortcollinsnow.com/article/20080523/NEWS/792549154 |work=Fort Collins Now |date=May 23, 2008 |accessdate=2008-06-13 }}</ref> and Timothy, the coach of the Colorado State University ultimate frisbee team.<ref name=\"votesmart\"/><ref name=\"sitebio\"/>\n\n==Legislative career==\n\n===2004 and 2006 campaigns===\nKefalas first ran for the state legislature in 2004, winning the Democratic Party primary by only seven votes over Fort Collins councilman [[Bill Bertschy]] after a recount process that lasted for several weeks.<ref name=\"assured\">{{cite news |title=Recount assured in Colorado legislative primary |work=Associated Press |date=August 25, 2004 }}</ref> Kefalas lost the general election by fewer than 500 votes to incumbent [[United States Republican Party|Republican]] [[Bob McCluskey]] in a race that also included [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]] candidate [[Jassen Bowman]]. Kefalas ran unchallenged for the Democratic nomination in 2006, and narrowly prevailed over McCluskey in the general election.<ref name=\"larelect\">{{cite web|url=http://www.co.larimer.co.us/elections/elections_tab.htm |title=Election Information |accessdate=2007-03-14 |author=Larimer County, Colorado |work=Larimer County Virtual Courthouse |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070204090734/http://www.co.larimer.co.us/elections/elections_tab.htm |archivedate=2007-02-04 }}</ref>\n\n===2007 legislative session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Rep.\n|Name=Kefalas\n|Year=2007\n|Bill Number 1=HB07-1026\n|Bill Link 1= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/1A2EE2E2BA4F8DD687257251007D5362?Open&file=1026_enr.pdf\n|Bill Title 1=Concerning health insurance at institutions of higher education \n|Bill Status 1=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Link 2=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/937219E477BFB24087257251007C799F?Open&file=1131_enr.pdf \n|Bill Number 2=HB07-1131 \n|Bill Title 2=Concerning standards for hemodialysis technicians as part of the state regulation of dialysis treatment clinics [...]\n|Bill Status 2=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Link 3=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/784A26974342B8C087257251007D5690?Open&file=1162_01.pdf \n|Bill Number 3=HB07-1162] \n|Bill Title 3=Concerning [...] creating a study group and pilot project on the use of instant runoff voting and other methods that allow voters to express preferences on multiple candidates\n|Bill Status 3=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Link 4=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/8AB27D5D41DC74B2872572580077C45B?Open&file=1220_enr.pdf \n|Bill Number 4=HB07-1220\n|Bill Title 4=Concerning a preference for the purchase of environmentally preferable products by governmental entities\n|Bill Status 4=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Link 5= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/4F8183141DD496C187257268007D1306?Open&file=1260_enr.pdf \n|Bill Number 5=HB07-1260\n|Bill Title 5=Concerning [...] changing the sunset review dates for the state board of nursing and the Colorado state board of chiropractic examiners\n|Bill Status 5=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Link 6=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/CFD09508DC8FE50987257264007B73C6?Open&file=1290_01.pdf \n|Bill Number 6=HB07-1290\n|Bill Title 6=Concerning the requirement that the Department of Revenue report on the impact of tax policy in a tax incidence study\n|Bill Status 6=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Link 7=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/0E920A50BBA41B348725728B0062A601?Open&file=1349_enr.pdf \n|Bill Number 7=HB07-1349\n|Bill Title 7=Concerning child support obligations, and making an appropriation in connection therewith\n|Bill Status 7=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n}}\n\nIn the 2007-2008 session of the Colorado General Assembly, Kefalas sat on the House Finance Committee and the House Health and Human Services Committee.<ref name=\"cmtes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/directory.nsf/HouCommWp?OpenView |title=House Committees of Reference |accessdate=2007-12-11 |work=Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>\n\nWhile in the legislature, he sponsored successful bills to encourage state purchasing of \"environmentally preferable\" products,<ref name=\"enviro\">{{cite news |first=Amy |last=Fletcher|title=Enviro purchasing bill gets preliminary OK |url=http://denver.bizjournals.com/denver/stories/2007/02/26/daily5.html |work=Denver Business Journal |date=February 26, 2007 |accessdate=2007-03-14 }}</ref> to allow [[Colorado State University]] to require graduate student health insurance,<ref name=\"health\">{{cite news |first=Jason |last=Kosena |title=Graduate-student health insurance bill moves forward |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070223/CSUZONE01/702230335/1110 |work=Denver Business Journal |date=February 23, 2007 |accessdate=2007-03-14 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> and to create licensing standards for [[hemodialysis]] technicians.<ref name=\"newmakers\"/>\n\nKefalas proposed a bill to explore alternative [[voting system]]s,<ref name=\"newmakers\">{{cite news |first=Kevin |last=Darst |title=New lawmakers make debut in Statehouse session |url=http://www.rmchronicle.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=296&Itemid=26  \n|work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=January 3, 2007 |accessdate=2007-03-14 }}</ref> which was defeated in committee,<ref name=\"unbowed\">{{cite news |first=Seth |last=Anthony |title=Defeated but unbowed |url=http://www.fairvote.org/?page=200&articlemode=showspecific&showarticle=2633  \n|work=Fort Collins Weekly |date=May 1, 2007 |accessdate=2007-07-12 }}</ref> but which led to the creation of an 11-member multi-partisan task force to study related issues.<ref name=\"system\">{{cite news |first=John |last=Kefalas |author2=Rick VanWie |author3=Julie Connor |title=New system would eliminate costly runoff elections |url=http://blogs.rockymountainnews.com/denver/speakout/2007/05/post_68.html |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=May 27, 2007 |accessdate=2007-07-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001015424/http://blogs.rockymountainnews.com/denver/speakout/2007/05/post_68.html |archivedate=October 1, 2007 }}</ref> Another of Kefalas' proposed bills, which would have required the Colorado Department of Revenue to regularly report on tax burdens across individual income groups, was also defeated in committee.<ref name=\"account3\">{{cite web |url=http://johnkefalas.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=173&Itemid=63 |title=Accountability Report #3 |accessdate=2007-03-14 |work=JohnKefalas.org |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071008214331/http://johnkefalas.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=173&Itemid=63 |archivedate = October 8, 2007}}</ref>\n\nDuring his first year in the legislature, Kefalas also founded the bipartisan Common Good Caucus to address poverty issues, and was a member of the Hispanic Caucus and the Diabetes/Obesity Caucus.<ref name=\"account8\">{{cite web |url=http://johnkefalas.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=188&Itemid=63\n |title=Accountability Report #8 |accessdate=2007-07-12 |work=JohnKefalas.org |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071008212921/http://johnkefalas.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=188&Itemid=63 |archivedate = October 8, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===2008 legislative session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Rep.\n|Name=Kefalas\n|Year=2008\n|Bill Number 1=HB08-1075\n|Bill Number 2=HB08-1161\n|Bill Number 3=HB08-1165\n|Bill Number 4=HB08-1207\n|Bill Number 5=HB08-1315\n|Bill Number 6=HB08-1340\n|Bill Number 7=HB08-1342\n|Bill Number 8=HB08-1362\n|Bill Number 9=HB08-1378\n|Bill Link 1=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/A6E239ADEC69821C872573A80067E98B?Open&file=1075_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 2=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/90D2CD3470EB25FC8725739F0082A568?Open&file=1161_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 3=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/3E56A272F107476B8725736800791976?Open&file=1165_01.pdf \n|Bill Link 4=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/79F09E1D4A7B6F84872573D300830CC2?Open&file=1207_enr.pdf \n|Bill Link 5=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/0E3D8068B9490FEF87257377005134C9?Open&file=1215_enr.pdf \n|Bill Link 6=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/DF4EC817F48D8032872573B0007E6F4D?Open&file=1340_01.pdf \n|Bill Link 7=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/96D52F2BFB4E25D3872573DF00479FE6?Open&file=1342_enr.pdf \n|Bill Link 8=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/1B2D8FC6C6D9889B87257375005D1BFA?Open&file=1362_01.pdf \n|Bill Link 9=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/3DE4F022372F448087257393005338B7?Open&file=1378_enr.pdf \n|Bill Title 1=Concerning the creation of a professional review committee by the meidcal staff of an ambulatory surgical center.\n|Bill Title 2=Concerning an increase in the regulatory authority of the Mined Land Reclamation Board over mining [...]\n|Bill Title 3=Concerning an increase in the regulatory authority of the Mined Land Reclamation Board over mining.\n|Bill Title 4=Concerning a purchasing preference for environmentally preferable products. \n|Bill Title 5=Concerning continuation of the authority of municipalities to contract with community health care providers.\n|Bill Title 6=Concerning the establishment of the Colorado Housing Investment Fund [...]\n|Bill Title 7=Concerning measures to improve child support enforcement [...]\n|Bill Title 8=Concerning the Earned Income Tax Credit [...]\n|Bill Title 9=Concerning the use of ranked voting methods, and [...] authorizing cities and special districts to use ranked voting.\n|Bill Status 1=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 2=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 3=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 4=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 5=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 6=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 7=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 8=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 9=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n}}\nIn the 2008 session of the Colorado General Assembly, Kefalas sat on the House Finance Committee and the House Health and Human Services Committee.<ref name=\"cmte2008\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/directory.nsf/HouCommWp?OpenView |title=House Committees of Reference |accessdate=2008-01-19 |work=Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>  Representative Kefalas was joined by [[Legislative staff in Colorado|chief of staff]] [[Anne Bellows]], a legal and civil rights expert.  For the 2008 legislative session, Kefalas worked with other Fort Collins legislators, particularly Rep. [[Randy Fischer]], on bills to increase scrutiny of proposed [[uranium]] mining operations.<ref name=\"acting\">{{cite news |first=John |last=Kefalas |author2=Randy Fischer |title=Legislators acting on residents' concerns |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070918/OPINION04/709180307/1014/CUSTOMERSERVICE02  \n|work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=September 18, 2007 |accessdate=2007-10-21 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref name=\"mounting\">\n{{cite news |first=Kevin |last=Duggan |title=Uranium mine faces mounting pressure |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=2007710170330 \n|work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=October 17, 2007 |accessdate=2007-10-21 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> While one bill, which would require that groundwater quality be restored following mining operations, passed the state legislature<ref name=\"fcnow\">{{cite news |first=Rebecca |last=Boyle |title=Uranium Bill Moves Forward Despite Heated Debate |url=http://www.fortcollinsnow.com/article/20080401/NEWS/227235752 |work=Fort Collins Now |date=April 1, 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-03 }}</ref><ref name=\"goesto\">{{cite news |first=Pamela |last=Dickman |title=Uranium mining bill goes to governor |url=http://www.reporterherald.com/news_story.asp?ID=16604 |work=[[Loveland Reporter-Herald]] |date=May 6, 2007 |accessdate=2008-05-06 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> and was signed into law,<ref name=\"rittersig\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=Gov. Bill Ritter signs uranium bill |url=http://www.greeleytrib.com/article/20080520/NEWS/875626312 |work=Greeley Tribune |date=May 20, 2008 |accessdate=2008-06-13 }}</ref> another measure, which would have created stronger public disclosure requirements for mining operations, was killed in committee,<ref name=\"nosec\">{{cite news |first=Andrew |last=Villegas |title=House Ag committee says no to second uranium bill |url=http://www.greeleytrib.com/article/20080403/NEWS/985078923 |work=Greeley Tribune |date=April 3, 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-03 }}</ref> but later revived in the state senate.<ref name=\"revived\">{{cite news |first=Rebecca |last=Boyle |title=Inside Politics: Time is Running Out for State Lawmakers |url=http://www.fortcollinsnow.com/article/20080502/POLITICS03/248506458 |work=Fort Collins Now |date=May 2, 2008 |accessdate=2008-05-02 }}</ref>\n\nWith Sen. [[Ron Tupa]], Kefalas was the house sponsor of legislation designed to reduce the cost of college [[textbook]]s by requiring textbook publishers to disclose costs and offer textbooks [[Product bundling|unbundled]] from additional materials,<ref name=\"tupa\">{{cite news |first=Brittany |last=Anas |title=Tupa backs curbing costs for books |url=http://dailycamera.com/news/2007/nov/18/tupa-backs-curbing-costs-textbook-prices/ \n|work=Boulder Daily Camera |date=November 18, 2007 |accessdate=2007-11-18 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071120134112/http://www.dailycamera.com/news/2007/nov/18/tupa-backs-curbing-costs-textbook-prices/ |archivedate = November 20, 2007}}</ref> and he sponsored legislation to allow outpatient surgery centers to establish [[peer review]] committees;<ref name=\"peer\">{{cite press release | title=Bill Improves Quality of Care and Patient Safety | publisher=Colorado House Democrats | date=January 25, 2008 | url=http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2008/01/bill-improves-q.html | accessdate=2008-02-23 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100511023709/http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2008/01/bill-improves-q.html | archivedate=May 11, 2010 }}</ref> both bills were signed into law by Gov. Ritter.<ref name=\"boating\">{{cite news |first=Rebecca |last=Boyle |title=Inside Politics: Lawmakers Take on Boating, Booze and Obesity |url=http://www.fortcollinsnow.com/article/20080404/GUEST/845113209 |work=Fort Collins Now |date=April 4, 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-10 }}</ref><ref name=\"signstext\">{{cite news |first=Brittany |last=Anas |title=Ritter signs textbook bill |url=http://dailycamera.com/news/2008/apr/08/ritter-signs-textbook-bill-law/ |work=Boulder Daily Camer |date=April 8, 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-10 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080413010224/http://dailycamera.com/news/2008/apr/08/ritter-signs-textbook-bill-law/ |archivedate = April 13, 2008}}</ref> For his support of ambulatory surgical centers, Kefalas was awarded the Legislator of the Year Award by the Colorado Ambulatory Surgery Center Association later that year.<ref name=\"ambul\">{{cite press release |title=Rep. John Kefalas Named Legislator of the Year by Colorado Ambulatory Surgery Center Association |date=9 September 2008 |publisher=Colorado House Democrats |url=http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2008/09/rep-john-kefalas-named-legislator-of-the-year-by-colorado-ambulatory-surgery-center-association.html |accessdate=2008-10-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100511013757/http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2008/09/rep-john-kefalas-named-legislator-of-the-year-by-colorado-ambulatory-surgery-center-association.html |archivedate=11 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\nKefalas also sponsored a bill to authorize local pilot tests of [[Instant-runoff voting|ranked choice]] [[voting methods]].<ref name=\"rank\">{{cite news |first=John |last=Ingold |title=House bill allows voters to rank candidates on ballot |url=http://www.denverpost.com/politics/ci_8686125 |work=Denver Post |date=March 25, 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-03 }}</ref> Kefalas sponsored a bill to establish a Colorado Housing Investment Fund,<ref name=\"chif\">{{cite news |first=John |last=Kefalas |title=Expectations high moving into new year |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=2008801010305 \n|work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=January 1, 2008 |accessdate=2007-12-02 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>  but withdrew the bill when proponents moved forward with a similar ballot initiative. He later expressed frustration when plans for the ballot measure were withdrawn.<ref name=\"killtheir\">{{cite news |first=Naomi |last=Zeveloff |title=Affordable housing activists kill their own statewide initiative |url=http://www.coloradoindependent.com/view/affordable-housing |work=Durango Herald |date=July 2, 2008 |accessdate=2008-08-05 }}</ref> Building on his 2007 bill to allow purchasing of \"green\" products, Kefalas also sponsored a measure to require Colorado governments to consider products' expected life and cost of ownership in making purchasing decisions,<ref name=\"expgreen\">{{cite press release | title=Lawmaker Expands \"Green\" Buying Program | publisher=Colorado House Democrats | date=February 18, 2008 | url=http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2008/02/lawmaker-expand.html | accessdate=2008-02-23 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100511061226/http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2008/02/lawmaker-expand.html | archivedate=May 11, 2010 }}</ref> which was signed into law.<ref name=\"newlaws\">{{cite press release|title=New Laws To Benefit Businesses and Consumers - Aug. 5 |date=July 31, 2008 |publisher=Colorado House Democrats |url=http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2008/07/new-laws-to-benefit-businesses-and-consumers---aug-5.html |accessdate=2008-08-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080817064942/http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2008/07/new-laws-to-benefit-businesses-and-consumers---aug-5.html |archivedate=August 17, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nAmong Kefalas' top priorities is restoring and expanding Colorado's [[earned income tax credit]],<ref name=\"working\">{{cite news |first=Elizabeth |last=Aguilera |title=Working poor seek tax credit from state |url=http://www.denverpost.com/frontpage/ci_5655555  \n|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=April 13, 2007 |accessdate=2007-07-12 }}</ref> a move which met with resistance from legislative leaders in 2007 due to budget constraints.<ref name=\"reinstate\">{{cite news |first=Jason |last=Kosena |title=Kefalas seeks to reinstate tax credit |url=http://www.denverpost.com/frontpage/ci_5655555  \n|work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=June 14, 2007 |accessdate=2007-07-12 }}</ref> Kefalas introduced a bill in the 2008 session to restore Colorado's EITC at ten percent of the federal credit,<ref name=\"carbon\">{{cite news |first=Brian |last=Park |title=Carbon Conqueror  |url=http://www.rmchronicle.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1757&Itemid=61\n|work=Rocky Mountain Chronicle |date=December 20, 2007 |accessdate=2007-12-20 }}</ref><ref name=\"briefs\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=Kefalas bill would restore tax credit |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080314/NEWS01/803140338/1002/CUSTOMERSERVICE02 |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=March 14, 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-03 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> but the bill was defeated in a House committee.<ref name=\"restore\">{{cite news |first=Perry |last=Swanson |title=Measure to restore state's Earned Income Tax Credit dies in committee |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/credit_34879___article.html/state_families.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=April 2, 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724190627/http://www.gazette.com/articles/credit_34879___article.html/state_families.html |archivedate=July 24, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===2008 election===\nHolding office in a closely contested district, Kefalas was expected to be targeted by Colorado Republicans during his 2008 re-election bid,<ref name=\"target\">{{cite news |first=Jason |last=Kosena |title=Kefalas a Republican target in 2008? |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070627/BLOGS02/70627010  \n|work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=June 27, 2007 |accessdate=2007-07-12 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> which he formally announced in January 2008.<ref name=\"reelect\">{{cite news |first=Jason |last=Kosena |title=Kefalas announces re-election bid |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080109/BLOGS02/80109027  \n|work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=January 9, 2008 |accessdate=2007-12-09 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Since taking office, Kefalas sought to maintain a dialogue with constituents by leading a series of monthly \"community conversations\" on topics ranging from health care to [[mobile home]] parks,<ref name=\"account8\"/><ref name=\"running\">{{cite web |url=http://squarestate.net/showDiary.do?diaryId=5066 |title=HD-52: John Kefalas running for re-election |accessdate=2008-01-09 |work=SquareState.net |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724081539/http://squarestate.net/showDiary.do?diaryId=5066 |archivedate=2011-07-24 }}</ref> and named sustainable economic development his top priority in office.<ref name=\"hopefuls\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=District 52 hopefuls respond |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20081019/NEWS03/810190330&s=d&page=2#pluckcomments |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=19 October 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-02 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nFormer Rep. [[Bob McCluskey]] announced his intention to run against Kefalas in February 2008, pitting the two against each other for the third time in as many election cycles<ref name=\"square\">{{cite news |first=Jason |last=Kosena |title=Kefalas, McCluskey to square off again in November |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080215/NEWS01/802150337/1002/CUSTOMERSERVICE02\n|work=Fort Collins COloradoan |date=February 15, 2008 |accessdate=2008-02-15 }}</ref> and creating a competitive race in what was seen as one of Colorado's \"swing\" districts.<ref name=\"mccl\">{{cite news |first=Jason |last=Kosena |title=HD 52: McCluskey looks to return to statehouse after see-saw races |url=http://coloradoindependent.com/14078/hd-52-mccluskey-looks-to-return-to-statehouse-after-see-saw-races |work=Colorado Independent |date=4 November 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-15 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the campaign, Kefalas held a fundraising advantage over McCluskey, with $60,000 cash on hand &mdash; three times as much as McCluskey &mdash; in mid-September.<ref name=\"cash\">{{cite news |first=Nate |last=Taylor |title=John Kefalas enjoys comfortable money lead over Bob McCluskey in HD 52 |url=http://coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080912/UPDATES01/80912007/1131/WINDSORBEACON01 |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=12 September 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-01 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> By late October, Kefalas had raised over $100,000, about $15,000 short of McCluskey's fundraising total;<ref name=\"exlaw\">{{cite news |first=David |last=Montero |title=Ex-lawmaker wants job back |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/oct/27/ex-lawmaker-wants-job-back/ |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=27 October 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-01 }}</ref> which included $65,000 that McCluskey donated to his own campaign.<ref name=\"buckle\">{{cite news |first=Nate |last=Taylor |title=Candidates buckle down |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20081030/NEWS03/810300324 |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=30 October 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-02 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nMcCluskey targeted Kefalas with a [[direct mail]] advertisement blaming Kefalas and the Democratic state legislature for high gasoline prices, a tactic Kefalas dismissed as \"negative campaigning.\"<ref name=\"gaspr\">{{cite news |first=Nate |last=Taylor |title=New ad targets Kefalas over gas prices |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080927/NEWS03/809270331/1002/CUSTOMERSERVICE02 |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=27 September 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-01 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Kefalas also condemned independent ads attacking McCluskey's legislative record as having \"crossed the line of civility.\"<ref name=\"ad527\">{{cite news |first=Nate |last=Taylor |title=527 ads attack McCluskey |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20081022/UPDATES01/81022037/1002/NEWS01 |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=22 October 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-01 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> The [[527 group]] Accountability for Colorado also spent over $50,000 in support of Kefalas' re-election,<ref name=\"buckle\"/> including mailers attacking McCluskey's legislative record; Kefalas also expressed disapproval of these advertisements.<ref name=\"battlespec\">{{cite news |first=Trevor |last=Simonton |title=Kefalas, McCluskey battle special interests, negative advertisements |url=http://media.www.collegian.com/media/storage/paper864/news/2008/10/31/News/Kefalas.Mccluskey.Battle.Special.Interests.Negative.Advertisements-3518336.shtml |work=Rocky Mountain Collegian |date=31 October 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205072540/http://media.www.collegian.com/media/storage/paper864/news/2008/10/31/News/Kefalas.Mccluskey.Battle.Special.Interests.Negative.Advertisements-3518336.shtml |archivedate=5 December 2008 }}</ref>\n\nMcCluskey's bid to unseat Kefalas was endorsed by the ''[[Denver Post]]'',<ref name=\"dphouse\">{{cite news |author=Editorial Board |title=Post's picks in Colorado's House of Representatives |url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_10741559 |work=Denver Post |date=17 October 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-01 }}\n</ref> while Kefalas was endorsed by the ''[[Windsor Beacon]]'' and the ''[[Fort Collins Coloradoan]]''.<ref name=\"csend\">{{cite news |first=Wendy |last=Norris |author2=Bob Spencer |title=State candidate endorsement watch |url=http://coloradoindependent.com/11911/state-candidate-endorsement-watch |work=Colorado Independent |date=3 November 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-07 }}</ref> Kefalas ultimately won a second term with about 59 percent of the popular vote,<ref name=\"bg52\">{{cite news |first=Jason |last=Kosena |title=Battleground HD 52 stays in Democratic hands |url=http://coloradoindependent.com/14403/battleground-hd-52-stays-in-democratic-hands |work=Colorado Independent |date=6 November 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-16 }}</ref><ref name=\"gen08\">{{cite web|url=http://coreports.ezvotetally.com/Reserved.ReportViewerWebControl.axd?ReportSession=jexpso55dlbays450fyzrmb4&ControlID=3a1b317069f040849b2b689d78addfc9&Culture=1033&UICulture=1033&ReportStack=1&OpType=ReportArea&Controller=dnn_ctr376_ViewRS2005_ReportViewer1&PageNumber=1&ZoomMode=Percent&ZoomPct=100&ReloadDocMap=true&SearchStartPage=0&LinkTarget=_top |title=Colorado Statewide Cumulative Report - 2008 General Election |accessdate=2008-12-04 |work=Colorado Secretary of State }}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> becoming the first Democrat to win re-election in the east Fort Collins district since 1936.<ref name=\"thankyous\">{{cite news |first=Rebecca |last=Boyle |title=It's Thank Yous All Around for FC Dems |url=http://www.fortcollinsnow.com/article/20081104/NEWS/811049962/1062&ParentProfile=1054&title=It's%20Thank%20Yous%20All%20Around%20for%20FC%20Dems |work=Fort Collins Now |date=4 November 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-16 }}</ref><ref name=\"successrare\">{{cite news |first=Nate |last=Taylor |title=Dem success rare in county |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/article/20081107/NEWS03/811070348/1002/CUSTOMERSERVICE02 |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=7 November 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-16 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n===2009 legislative session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Rep.\n|Name=Kefalas\n|Year=2009\n|Bill Number 1=HB09-1064\n|Bill Number 2=HB09-1105\n|Bill Number 3=HB09-1134\n|Bill Number 4=HB09-1251\n|Bill Number 5=HB09-1273\n|Bill Link 1=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2009a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/F05E81CDDCB2622587257537001A2A51?Open&file=1064_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 2=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2009a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/5F10F2ACE5B377238725753C007B97C1?Open&file=1105_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 3=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2009a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/CBD8440EA56F25038725753900757E9E?Open&file=1134_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 4=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2009a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/C20BC9AA013B97C38725753C00709A97?Open&file=1251_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 5=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2009a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/E5CFE643118E61458725754A007B14D2?Open&file=1273_eng.pdf\n|Bill Title 1=Concerning [...] establishing the Economic Opportunity Poverty Reduction Task Force for the purpose of advancing economic opportunity while reducing child and family poverty.\n|Bill Title 2=Concerning the creation of the Colorado Innovation Investment Tax Credit [...]\n|Bill Title 3=Concerning the Colorado Railroad Authority, and [...] creating the authority for the purpose of planning, designing, developing, financing, constructing, operating, and maintaining a passenger rail system [...]\n|Bill Title 4=Concerning the disclosure of criminal justice records.\n|Bill Title 5=Concerning the creation of a health care authority that shall be the administrator for health care services in Colorado.\n|Bill Status 1=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 2=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 3=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 4=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 5=Laid over on third reading in House\n}}\n\nFor the 2009 legislative session, Kefalas was named to seats on the House Appropriations Committee, the House Finance Committee, and the House Health and Human Services Committee.<ref name=\"cmte09\">{{cite press release|title=House Democrats Unveil 2009 Committee Chairs & Assignments |date=18 November 2008 |publisher=Colorado House Democrats |url=http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2008/11/house-democrats-unveil-2009-committee-chairs-assignments.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103101139/http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2008/11/house-democrats-unveil-2009-committee-chairs-assignments.html |archivedate= 3 January 2010 }}</ref> Kefalas has named health care reform as his top priority and planned on introducing legislation to create a [[single-payer universal health care]] system in Colorado during the 2009 session.<ref name=\"advancek\">{{cite news |first=Pat |last=Ferrier |title=Kefalas to advance statewide insurance |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/article/20081206/BUSINESS/812060319 |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=6 December 2008 |accessdate=2008-12-06 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref name=\"comprehen\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=Kefalas readies comprehensive health-care bill |url=http://www.ncbr.com/article.asp?id=97568 |work=Northern Colorado Business Report |date=9 December 2008 |accessdate=2008-12-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714161811/http://www.ncbr.com/article.asp?id=97568 |archive-date=14 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The bill was introduced as a proposal to create a 23-member commission to make recommendations as to how to implement a single-payer system, and was reported favorably out of a House committee.<ref name=\"revamp\">{{cite news |first=Bob |last=Mook\n|title=Bill to revamp Colorado health care system advances |url=http://denver.bizjournals.com/denver/stories/2009/03/16/daily46.html |work=Denver Business Journal |date=18 March 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-24}}\n</ref><ref name=\"canadian\">{{cite news |first=Tim |last=Hoover\n|title=Bill backing Canadian-type health plan gains in Colo. House |url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_11945054 |work=Denver Post |date=19 March 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-24}}</ref> However, Kefalas was one vote short of the 33 necessary to pass the legislation out of the house, and in April, asked that the legislation be killed.<ref name=\"fails\">{{cite news |first=Joe |last=Hanel |title=State single-payer health-care effort fails |url=http://durangoherald.com/sections/News/2009/04/16/State_singlepayer_healthcare_effort_fails/ |work=Durango Herald |date=16 April 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090419214654/http://durangoherald.com/sections/News/2009/04/16/State%5Fsinglepayer%5Fhealthcare%5Feffort%5Ffails/ |archive-date=2009-04-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nKefalas also sponsored the Colorado Innovation Investment Tax Credit,<ref name=\"transform\">{{cite news |first=Kristen |last=Tatti |title=2009 was 'transformational' year for RMI2 |url=http://ncbr.com/article.asp?id=103470 |work=Northern Colorado Business Report |date=18 December 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102140406/http://ncbr.com/article.asp?id=103470 |archive-date=2 January 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> legislation to create $750,000 in tax credits for [[angel investor]]s in startup companies,<ref name=\"lowbudget\">{{cite news |first=Bob |last=Mook |title='Low-budget' ideas given to legislators |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/denver/stories/2008/12/08/daily17.html |work=Denver Business Journal |date=8 December 2008 |accessdate=2008-12-25 }}</ref><ref name=\"inside2\">{{cite news |first=Rebecca |last=Boyle\n|title=Inside Politics (Part 2): Activists Color Their Legislative Agenda |url=http://www.fortcollinsnow.com/article/20090204/NEWS/902049983/1026/NONE&title=Inside%20Politics%20(Part%202):%20%20Activists%20Color%20Their%20Legislative%20Agenda |work=Fort Collins Now |date=4 December 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-24}}</ref><ref name=\"angels\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover\n|title=New Colorado laws benefit tech investors, boost energy loans \n|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/denver/stories/2009/08/31/daily45.html |work=Denver Business Journal |date=1 September 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-24}}</ref> to increase support for [[job training]] programs,<ref name=\"coalitionforce\">{{cite news |first=Pat |last=Ferrier |title=Northern Colorado coalition pitches work force initiative |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/article/20081223/BUSINESS/812230321/1046 |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=23 December 2008 |accessdate=2008-12-26 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> and to create a Colorado Railroad Authority to begin planning for statewide [[passenger rail]] service.<ref name=\"passrail\">{{cite news |first=Charles |last=Ashby |title=Passenger rail service bills on track |url=http://www.chieftain.com/articles/2009/01/25/news/denver_bureau/doc497c08c320ec7020554294.txt |work=Pueblo Chieftain |date=25 January 2009 |accessdate=2009-02-22 }}</ref>\n\nKefalas also sponsored legislation to create an Economic Opportunity/Poverty Reduction Task Force,<ref name=\"milrem\">{{cite news\n |first=Kathryn \n |last=Dailey \n |title=Bill regarding military remains now in state Senate \n |url=http://www.reporterherald.com/news_story.asp?ID=21320 \n |work=Loveland Reporter-Herald \n |date=2 February 2009 \n |accessdate=2009-07-03 \n}}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"agendas\">{{cite news |first=Terrance |last=Carroll\n|title=Capitol Agendas |url=http://www.chieftain.com/articles/2009/03/15/editorial/doc49bc683ee3ac6255989846.txt |work=Pueblo Chieftain |date=15 March 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-24}}\n</ref> which he chaired following the regular session.<ref>{{cite news |first=Tina |last=Griego |title=Griego: Panel's hard knocks may open doors |url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_13164705 |work=Denver Post |date=20 August 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> The committee's objective is to develop plans to reduce Colorado's poverty rate by half in ten years, examining a broad range of issues from economic development to education to transportation to tax policy,<ref name=\"reduce\">{{cite news |author=Staff Report |title=Colo. task force looks for ways to reduce poverty |url=http://www.summitdaily.com/article/20090727/NEWS/907279979/1078&ParentProfile=1055 |work=Summit Daily News |date=27 July 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224015513/http://www.summitdaily.com/article/20090727/NEWS/907279979/1078%26ParentProfile%3D1055 |archive-date=24 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and it considered potential legislation on topics ranging from the [[earned income tax credit]] to [[rent control]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Stephen K. |last=Paulson |title=Colo. lawmakers consider measures to cut poverty |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/businesstechnology/2010100970_apusreducingpovertycolorado.html |work=Seattle Times |date=20 October 2009 |accessdate=2010-01-04}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the legislation session, Kefalas was the only male legislator honored with the Colorado Lawmakers Award by the Denver Women\u2019s Commission and the Colorado Women\u2019s Chamber of Commerce.<ref name=\"menwomen\">{{cite press release |title=Rep. John Kefalas, A Man Among Women! |date=3 November 2009 |publisher=Colorado House Democrats |url=http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2009/11/rep-john-kefalas-a-man-among-women.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091110163127/http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2009/11/rep-john-kefalas-a-man-among-women.html |archivedate=10 November 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===2010 election===\nIn August 2009, Kefalas announced his intention to seek a third term in the legislature in the November 2010 legislative elections.<ref name=\"frontra\">{{cite news |author=Staff Report |title=Front Range Briefs |url=http://www.reporterherald.com/news_story.asp?id=24556 |work=Loveland Reporter Herald |date=23 August 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-24 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  Kefalas was reelected with 57% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|title=CBS Election Results|url=http://elections.cbslocal.com/cbs/kcnc/20101102/race85.shtml|work=CBS Election Results|accessdate=11 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2012 election===\nRepresentative Kefalas announced that he would seek election to the [[Colorado Senate|state senate]] seat vacated by [[Bob Bacon]].  Kefalas' bid was endorsed by The [[Fort Collins Coloradoan]] and several former elected officials.<ref>{{cite web|title=John Kefalas - Endorsements|url=http://www.johnkefalas.org/endorsements|access-date=2012-11-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102212320/http://www.johnkefalas.org/endorsements|archive-date=2012-11-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>  In the [[United States elections, 2012|2012 General Election]], Representative Kefalas faced Republican challenger [[Syndi Anderson]] for the open Senate seat.  Kefalas was elected by a wide margin of 58% to 36% with the remainder of the vote going to third-party candidates.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://results.enr.clarityelections.com/CO/43032/111283/en/summary.html# |title=CO - Election Results - Colorado Secretary of State |access-date=2012-11-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314203900/http://results.enr.clarityelections.com/CO/43032/111283/en/summary.html |archive-date=2017-03-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://data.denverpost.com/election/results/state-house/2012/ |title=State House 2012 Election Results - Denver Post}}</ref>  Senator Kefalas now represents the people of State Senate District 14.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://leg.colorado.gov/legislators/john-kefalas John Kefalas profile, Colorado General Assembly]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20171202105134/http://www.johnkefalas.org/ State Rep. John Kefalas]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071009002444/http://www.kefalas2008.com/ John Kefalas 2008 campaign]\n* [https://www.myspace.com/johnkefalas John Kefalas MySpace page]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kefalas, John}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Greek emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Fairleigh Dickinson University alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the Colorado House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Fort Collins, Colorado]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Colorado state senators]]\n[[Category:County commissioners in Colorado]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox State Representative \n| name=John Kefalas\n| image name=Colorado-Rep-John-Kefalas.jpg\n| state_senate=Colorado\n| state=Colorado\n| district=14th\n| term_start=2013\n| term_end=January 4, 2019\n| preceded=[[Bob Bacon]]\n| succeeded=[[Joann Ginal]]\n| state_house2=Colorado\n| state2=Colorado\n| district2=52nd\n| term_start2=January 10, 2007\n| term_end2=November 6, 2012\n| preceded2=[[Bob McCluskey]]\n| succeeded2=[[Joann Ginal]]\n| birth_date={{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1954|12|26}}\n| birth_place=[[Piraeus, Greece]]\n| death_date=\n| death_place=\n| spouse=Beth\n| profession=Activist, Legislator\n| party=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|}}\n\n'''John Michael Kefalas''' (born December 26, 1954<ref name=\"votesmart\">{{cite web |url=http://www.vote-smart.org/bio.php?can_id=29946 |title=Representative John Michael Kefalas |accessdate=2007-03-14 |work=Project Vote Smart }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>) is a politician in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Colorado]]. An educator and lobbyist before first running for the legislature in 2004, Kefalas defeated a Republican incumbent to win election to the [[Colorado House of Representatives]] as a [[United States Democratic Party|Democrat]] in 2006.  Kefalas won election to the [[Colorado Senate|State Senate]] in 2012 and represented Senate District 14 until early 2019. In 2018, Kefalas ran for and won a seat on the [[Larimer County, Colorado|Larimer County]] [[County commission|Board of County Commissioners]]. He resigned his Senate seat, and a vacancy committee nominated [[Joann Ginal]] to replace him.<ref>{{cite news |last=Coltrain |first=Nick |date=2019-01-04 |title=Fort Collins legislators seek to pursue progressive goals while avoiding voter backlash |url=https://www.coloradoan.com/story/news/2019/01/04/jeni-arndt-joann-ginal-set-stage-2019-colorado-legislature-session/2483017002/ |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan  |location= |access-date=2019-01-05 }}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life, education, and career===\nBorn in [[Piraeus, Greece]],<ref name=\"votesmart\"/> Kefalas earned a bachelor's degree in [[botany]]<ref name=\"chal52\">{{cite news |first=Nate |last=Taylor |title=Changing political landscape challenges HD52 contenders |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080703/NEWS01/807030335/1002/CUSTOMERSERVICE02 |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=July 3, 2008 |accessdate=2008-08-05 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> from [[Colorado State University]] in 1978 and then joined the [[Peace Corps]] in 1979, serving as an agricultural extension worker in [[El Salvador]].<ref name=\"votesmart\"/> After returning to the United States, he earned a master's degree in teaching, with a secondary science specialization from [[Fairleigh Dickinson University]]<ref name=\"chal52\"/> in 1982 and taught in the [[Poudre School District]]. He has also worked as an employment counselor for [[Larimer County, Colorado]], and as a health outreach worker.<ref name=\"votesmart\"/>\n\n===Public service and volunteerism===\nFrom 1997 to 2004, Kefalas worked as a public policy advocate and community development coordinator for [[Catholic Charities]]<ref name=\"char\">{{cite news |first=Jill |last=Chodak |title=Community, Coopersmith's feed the needy for Christmas |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/article/20081225/UPDATES01/81225006 |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=25 December 2008 |accessdate=2008-12-27 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> until his departure amidst a controversy regarding his public support for ''[[Roe v. Wade]]'' and [[abortion]] rights during his 2004 legislative campaign.<ref name=\"catholic\">{{cite news |first=Ted |last=Olsen |title=Colorado candidate: Catholic Charities fired me over abortion support |url=http://ctlibrary.com/11912 |work=Christianity Today |date=August 1, 2004 |accessdate=2007-11-13 }}</ref> Before entering the legislature, he directed the Colorado Progressive Coalition's Tax Fairness Project.<ref name=\"sitebio\">{{cite web |url=http://johnkefalas.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=12&Itemid=64 |title=About John |accessdate=2007-03-14 |work=JohnKefalas.org |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071008212703/http://johnkefalas.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=12&Itemid=64 |archivedate = October 8, 2007 }}</ref> He has served as a member of the Fort Collins Housing Authority and the Colorado Social Legislation Committee,<ref name=\"votesmart\"/> and, in 2001, won the City of Fort Collins Human Relations Award.<ref name=\"hra\">{{cite web |url=http://fcgov.com/hra/kefalas.php |title=John Kefalas |accessdate=2007-07-13 |work=City of Fort Collins |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060219052903/http://fcgov.com/hra/kefalas.php |archivedate = February 19, 2006}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1980 to 1994, Kefalas redirected a portion of his federal income taxes to charitable organizations<ref name=\"qmark\">{{cite news |first=Erin |last=Rosa |title=Caught in the question mark| url=http://www.rmchronicle.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=63&Itemid=26 |work=Rocky Mountain Chronicle |date=November 14, 2006 |accessdate=2007-07-12 }}</ref> as a protest against United States military actions in Central America. He has paid his income taxes in full since 1994, but continued to boycott the [[federal telephone excise tax]] as recently as 2004. As a result, Kefalas has had a [[lien]] filed him and has had wages [[garnishment|garnished]]. Kefalas has paid his back taxes and considers his actions to be a conscientious protest.<ref name=\"peacecorps\"/> He has also written about his experience of \"war tax resistance\" for the newsletter of the [[National War Tax Resistance Coordinating Committee]].<ref name=\"compl\">{{cite news |first=John |last=Kefalas |title=War Tax Resistance -- Part of the Complete Package | url=http://www.nwtrcc.org/mtap01/mtap0201.htm#Persp |work=More Than a Paycheck: News from the War Tax Resistance Movement |date=February 2001 |accessdate=2007-12-29 }}</ref> In both his 2004 and 2006 legislative campaigns, Kefalas was accused of avoiding his federal tax obligation, both by his Republican opponent and by independent political committees.<ref name=\"dirty\">\n{{cite news |first=Greg |last=Campbell |title=John Kefalas alleges dirty tactics | url=http://peacecorpsonline.org/messages/messages/467/2057191.html |work=Fort Collins Weekly |date=August 30, 2006 |accessdate=2007-12-29 }}</ref><ref name=\"real\">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mGKX36EBaMU |title=The Real John Kefalas |accessdate=2007-12-29 |work=YouTube }}</ref> Kefalas has also been an outspoken opponent of the [[Iraq War]], and has engaged in non-violent civil disobedience in protest of the war.<ref name=\"peacecorps\">{{cite news |first=Matthew |last=Benson |title=Candidate Kefalas skips taxes in protest |url=http://peacecorpsonline.org/messages/messages/467/2022859.html |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=August 5, 2004 |accessdate=2007-03-14 }}</ref>\n\nKefalas is married; he and his wife Beth have two sons &mdash; Harlan, an active-duty U.S. Army soldier who has served in Iraq, Kosovo, and Afghanistan,<ref name=\"peacewar\">{{cite news |first=John |last=Kefalas |title=Kefalas: War, Peace and Family Values |url=http://www.fortcollinsnow.com/article/20080523/NEWS/792549154 |work=Fort Collins Now |date=May 23, 2008 |accessdate=2008-06-13 }}</ref> and Timothy, the coach of the Colorado State University ultimate frisbee team.<ref name=\"votesmart\"/><ref name=\"sitebio\"/>\n\n==Legislative career==\n\n===2004 and 2006 campaigns===\nKefalas first ran for the state legislature in 2004, winning the Democratic Party primary by only seven votes over Fort Collins councilman [[Bill Bertschy]] after a recount process that lasted for several weeks.<ref name=\"assured\">{{cite news |title=Recount assured in Colorado legislative primary |work=Associated Press |date=August 25, 2004 }}</ref> Kefalas lost the general election by fewer than 500 votes to incumbent [[United States Republican Party|Republican]] [[Bob McCluskey]] in a race that also included [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]] candidate [[Jassen Bowman]]. Kefalas ran unchallenged for the Democratic nomination in 2006, and narrowly prevailed over McCluskey in the general election.<ref name=\"larelect\">{{cite web|url=http://www.co.larimer.co.us/elections/elections_tab.htm |title=Election Information |accessdate=2007-03-14 |author=Larimer County, Colorado |work=Larimer County Virtual Courthouse |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070204090734/http://www.co.larimer.co.us/elections/elections_tab.htm |archivedate=2007-02-04 }}</ref>\n\n===2007 legislative session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Rep.\n|Name=Kefalas\n|Year=2007\n|Bill Number 1=HB07-1026\n|Bill Link 1= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/1A2EE2E2BA4F8DD687257251007D5362?Open&file=1026_enr.pdf\n|Bill Title 1=Concerning health insurance at institutions of higher education \n|Bill Status 1=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Link 2=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/937219E477BFB24087257251007C799F?Open&file=1131_enr.pdf \n|Bill Number 2=HB07-1131 \n|Bill Title 2=Concerning standards for hemodialysis technicians as part of the state regulation of dialysis treatment clinics [...]\n|Bill Status 2=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Link 3=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/784A26974342B8C087257251007D5690?Open&file=1162_01.pdf \n|Bill Number 3=HB07-1162] \n|Bill Title 3=Concerning [...] creating a study group and pilot project on the use of instant runoff voting and other methods that allow voters to express preferences on multiple candidates\n|Bill Status 3=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Link 4=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/8AB27D5D41DC74B2872572580077C45B?Open&file=1220_enr.pdf \n|Bill Number 4=HB07-1220\n|Bill Title 4=Concerning a preference for the purchase of environmentally preferable products by governmental entities\n|Bill Status 4=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Link 5= http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/4F8183141DD496C187257268007D1306?Open&file=1260_enr.pdf \n|Bill Number 5=HB07-1260\n|Bill Title 5=Concerning [...] changing the sunset review dates for the state board of nursing and the Colorado state board of chiropractic examiners\n|Bill Status 5=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Link 6=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/CFD09508DC8FE50987257264007B73C6?Open&file=1290_01.pdf \n|Bill Number 6=HB07-1290\n|Bill Title 6=Concerning the requirement that the Department of Revenue report on the impact of tax policy in a tax incidence study\n|Bill Status 6=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Link 7=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/0E920A50BBA41B348725728B0062A601?Open&file=1349_enr.pdf \n|Bill Number 7=HB07-1349\n|Bill Title 7=Concerning child support obligations, and making an appropriation in connection therewith\n|Bill Status 7=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n}}\n\nIn the 2007-2008 session of the Colorado General Assembly, Kefalas sat on the House Finance Committee and the House Health and Human Services Committee.<ref name=\"cmtes\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2007a/directory.nsf/HouCommWp?OpenView |title=House Committees of Reference |accessdate=2007-12-11 |work=Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>\n\nWhile in the legislature, he sponsored successful bills to encourage state purchasing of \"environmentally preferable\" products,<ref name=\"enviro\">{{cite news |first=Amy |last=Fletcher|title=Enviro purchasing bill gets preliminary OK |url=http://denver.bizjournals.com/denver/stories/2007/02/26/daily5.html |work=Denver Business Journal |date=February 26, 2007 |accessdate=2007-03-14 }}</ref> to allow [[Colorado State University]] to require graduate student health insurance,<ref name=\"health\">{{cite news |first=Jason |last=Kosena |title=Graduate-student health insurance bill moves forward |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070223/CSUZONE01/702230335/1110 |work=Denver Business Journal |date=February 23, 2007 |accessdate=2007-03-14 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> and to create licensing standards for [[hemodialysis]] technicians.<ref name=\"newmakers\"/>\n\nKefalas proposed a bill to explore alternative [[voting system]]s,<ref name=\"newmakers\">{{cite news |first=Kevin |last=Darst |title=New lawmakers make debut in Statehouse session |url=http://www.rmchronicle.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=296&Itemid=26  \n|work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=January 3, 2007 |accessdate=2007-03-14 }}</ref> which was defeated in committee,<ref name=\"unbowed\">{{cite news |first=Seth |last=Anthony |title=Defeated but unbowed |url=http://www.fairvote.org/?page=200&articlemode=showspecific&showarticle=2633  \n|work=Fort Collins Weekly |date=May 1, 2007 |accessdate=2007-07-12 }}</ref> but which led to the creation of an 11-member multi-partisan task force to study related issues.<ref name=\"system\">{{cite news |first=John |last=Kefalas |author2=Rick VanWie |author3=Julie Connor |title=New system would eliminate costly runoff elections |url=http://blogs.rockymountainnews.com/denver/speakout/2007/05/post_68.html |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=May 27, 2007 |accessdate=2007-07-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001015424/http://blogs.rockymountainnews.com/denver/speakout/2007/05/post_68.html |archivedate=October 1, 2007 }}</ref> Another of Kefalas' proposed bills, which would have required the Colorado Department of Revenue to regularly report on tax burdens across individual income groups, was also defeated in committee.<ref name=\"account3\">{{cite web |url=http://johnkefalas.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=173&Itemid=63 |title=Accountability Report #3 |accessdate=2007-03-14 |work=JohnKefalas.org |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071008214331/http://johnkefalas.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=173&Itemid=63 |archivedate = October 8, 2007}}</ref>\n\nDuring his first year in the legislature, Kefalas also founded the bipartisan Common Good Caucus to address poverty issues, and was a member of the Hispanic Caucus and the Diabetes/Obesity Caucus.<ref name=\"account8\">{{cite web |url=http://johnkefalas.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=188&Itemid=63\n |title=Accountability Report #8 |accessdate=2007-07-12 |work=JohnKefalas.org |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071008212921/http://johnkefalas.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=188&Itemid=63 |archivedate = October 8, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===2008 legislative session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Rep.\n|Name=Kefalas\n|Year=2008\n|Bill Number 1=HB08-1075\n|Bill Number 2=HB08-1161\n|Bill Number 3=HB08-1165\n|Bill Number 4=HB08-1207\n|Bill Number 5=HB08-1315\n|Bill Number 6=HB08-1340\n|Bill Number 7=HB08-1342\n|Bill Number 8=HB08-1362\n|Bill Number 9=HB08-1378\n|Bill Link 1=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/A6E239ADEC69821C872573A80067E98B?Open&file=1075_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 2=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/90D2CD3470EB25FC8725739F0082A568?Open&file=1161_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 3=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/3E56A272F107476B8725736800791976?Open&file=1165_01.pdf \n|Bill Link 4=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/79F09E1D4A7B6F84872573D300830CC2?Open&file=1207_enr.pdf \n|Bill Link 5=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/0E3D8068B9490FEF87257377005134C9?Open&file=1215_enr.pdf \n|Bill Link 6=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/DF4EC817F48D8032872573B0007E6F4D?Open&file=1340_01.pdf \n|Bill Link 7=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/96D52F2BFB4E25D3872573DF00479FE6?Open&file=1342_enr.pdf \n|Bill Link 8=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/1B2D8FC6C6D9889B87257375005D1BFA?Open&file=1362_01.pdf \n|Bill Link 9=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/3DE4F022372F448087257393005338B7?Open&file=1378_enr.pdf \n|Bill Title 1=Concerning the creation of a professional review committee by the meidcal staff of an ambulatory surgical center.\n|Bill Title 2=Concerning an increase in the regulatory authority of the Mined Land Reclamation Board over mining [...]\n|Bill Title 3=Concerning an increase in the regulatory authority of the Mined Land Reclamation Board over mining.\n|Bill Title 4=Concerning a purchasing preference for environmentally preferable products. \n|Bill Title 5=Concerning continuation of the authority of municipalities to contract with community health care providers.\n|Bill Title 6=Concerning the establishment of the Colorado Housing Investment Fund [...]\n|Bill Title 7=Concerning measures to improve child support enforcement [...]\n|Bill Title 8=Concerning the Earned Income Tax Credit [...]\n|Bill Title 9=Concerning the use of ranked voting methods, and [...] authorizing cities and special districts to use ranked voting.\n|Bill Status 1=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 2=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 3=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 4=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 5=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 6=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 7=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 8=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 9=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n}}\nIn the 2008 session of the Colorado General Assembly, Kefalas sat on the House Finance Committee and the House Health and Human Services Committee.<ref name=\"cmte2008\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2008a/directory.nsf/HouCommWp?OpenView |title=House Committees of Reference |accessdate=2008-01-19 |work=Colorado General Assembly}}</ref>  Representative Kefalas was joined by [[Legislative staff in Colorado|chief of staff]] [[Anne Bellows]], a legal and civil rights expert.  For the 2008 legislative session, Kefalas worked with other Fort Collins legislators, particularly Rep. [[Randy Fischer]], on bills to increase scrutiny of proposed [[uranium]] mining operations.<ref name=\"acting\">{{cite news |first=John |last=Kefalas |author2=Randy Fischer |title=Legislators acting on residents' concerns |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070918/OPINION04/709180307/1014/CUSTOMERSERVICE02  \n|work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=September 18, 2007 |accessdate=2007-10-21 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref name=\"mounting\">\n{{cite news |first=Kevin |last=Duggan |title=Uranium mine faces mounting pressure |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=2007710170330 \n|work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=October 17, 2007 |accessdate=2007-10-21 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> While one bill, which would require that groundwater quality be restored following mining operations, passed the state legislature<ref name=\"fcnow\">{{cite news |first=Rebecca |last=Boyle |title=Uranium Bill Moves Forward Despite Heated Debate |url=http://www.fortcollinsnow.com/article/20080401/NEWS/227235752 |work=Fort Collins Now |date=April 1, 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-03 }}</ref><ref name=\"goesto\">{{cite news |first=Pamela |last=Dickman |title=Uranium mining bill goes to governor |url=http://www.reporterherald.com/news_story.asp?ID=16604 |work=[[Loveland Reporter-Herald]] |date=May 6, 2007 |accessdate=2008-05-06 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref> and was signed into law,<ref name=\"rittersig\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=Gov. Bill Ritter signs uranium bill |url=http://www.greeleytrib.com/article/20080520/NEWS/875626312 |work=Greeley Tribune |date=May 20, 2008 |accessdate=2008-06-13 }}</ref> another measure, which would have created stronger public disclosure requirements for mining operations, was killed in committee,<ref name=\"nosec\">{{cite news |first=Andrew |last=Villegas |title=House Ag committee says no to second uranium bill |url=http://www.greeleytrib.com/article/20080403/NEWS/985078923 |work=Greeley Tribune |date=April 3, 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-03 }}</ref> but later revived in the state senate.<ref name=\"revived\">{{cite news |first=Rebecca |last=Boyle |title=Inside Politics: Time is Running Out for State Lawmakers |url=http://www.fortcollinsnow.com/article/20080502/POLITICS03/248506458 |work=Fort Collins Now |date=May 2, 2008 |accessdate=2008-05-02 }}</ref>\n\nWith Sen. [[Ron Tupa]], Kefalas was the house sponsor of legislation designed to reduce the cost of college [[textbook]]s by requiring textbook publishers to disclose costs and offer textbooks [[Product bundling|unbundled]] from additional materials,<ref name=\"tupa\">{{cite news |first=Brittany |last=Anas |title=Tupa backs curbing costs for books |url=http://dailycamera.com/news/2007/nov/18/tupa-backs-curbing-costs-textbook-prices/ \n|work=Boulder Daily Camera |date=November 18, 2007 |accessdate=2007-11-18 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071120134112/http://www.dailycamera.com/news/2007/nov/18/tupa-backs-curbing-costs-textbook-prices/ |archivedate = November 20, 2007}}</ref> and he sponsored legislation to allow outpatient surgery centers to establish [[peer review]] committees;<ref name=\"peer\">{{cite press release | title=Bill Improves Quality of Care and Patient Safety | publisher=Colorado House Democrats | date=January 25, 2008 | url=http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2008/01/bill-improves-q.html | accessdate=2008-02-23 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100511023709/http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2008/01/bill-improves-q.html | archivedate=May 11, 2010 }}</ref> both bills were signed into law by Gov. Ritter.<ref name=\"boating\">{{cite news |first=Rebecca |last=Boyle |title=Inside Politics: Lawmakers Take on Boating, Booze and Obesity |url=http://www.fortcollinsnow.com/article/20080404/GUEST/845113209 |work=Fort Collins Now |date=April 4, 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-10 }}</ref><ref name=\"signstext\">{{cite news |first=Brittany |last=Anas |title=Ritter signs textbook bill |url=http://dailycamera.com/news/2008/apr/08/ritter-signs-textbook-bill-law/ |work=Boulder Daily Camer |date=April 8, 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-10 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080413010224/http://dailycamera.com/news/2008/apr/08/ritter-signs-textbook-bill-law/ |archivedate = April 13, 2008}}</ref> For his support of ambulatory surgical centers, Kefalas was awarded the Legislator of the Year Award by the Colorado Ambulatory Surgery Center Association later that year.<ref name=\"ambul\">{{cite press release |title=Rep. John Kefalas Named Legislator of the Year by Colorado Ambulatory Surgery Center Association |date=9 September 2008 |publisher=Colorado House Democrats |url=http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2008/09/rep-john-kefalas-named-legislator-of-the-year-by-colorado-ambulatory-surgery-center-association.html |accessdate=2008-10-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100511013757/http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2008/09/rep-john-kefalas-named-legislator-of-the-year-by-colorado-ambulatory-surgery-center-association.html |archivedate=11 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\nKefalas also sponsored a bill to authorize local pilot tests of [[Instant-runoff voting|ranked choice]] [[voting methods]].<ref name=\"rank\">{{cite news |first=John |last=Ingold |title=House bill allows voters to rank candidates on ballot |url=http://www.denverpost.com/politics/ci_8686125 |work=Denver Post |date=March 25, 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-03 }}</ref> Kefalas sponsored a bill to establish a Colorado Housing Investment Fund,<ref name=\"chif\">{{cite news |first=John |last=Kefalas |title=Expectations high moving into new year |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=2008801010305 \n|work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=January 1, 2008 |accessdate=2007-12-02 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>  but withdrew the bill when proponents moved forward with a similar ballot initiative. He later expressed frustration when plans for the ballot measure were withdrawn.<ref name=\"killtheir\">{{cite news |first=Naomi |last=Zeveloff |title=Affordable housing activists kill their own statewide initiative |url=http://www.coloradoindependent.com/view/affordable-housing |work=Durango Herald |date=July 2, 2008 |accessdate=2008-08-05 }}</ref> Building on his 2007 bill to allow purchasing of \"green\" products, Kefalas also sponsored a measure to require Colorado governments to consider products' expected life and cost of ownership in making purchasing decisions,<ref name=\"expgreen\">{{cite press release | title=Lawmaker Expands \"Green\" Buying Program | publisher=Colorado House Democrats | date=February 18, 2008 | url=http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2008/02/lawmaker-expand.html | accessdate=2008-02-23 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100511061226/http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2008/02/lawmaker-expand.html | archivedate=May 11, 2010 }}</ref> which was signed into law.<ref name=\"newlaws\">{{cite press release|title=New Laws To Benefit Businesses and Consumers - Aug. 5 |date=July 31, 2008 |publisher=Colorado House Democrats |url=http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2008/07/new-laws-to-benefit-businesses-and-consumers---aug-5.html |accessdate=2008-08-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080817064942/http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2008/07/new-laws-to-benefit-businesses-and-consumers---aug-5.html |archivedate=August 17, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nAmong Kefalas' top priorities is restoring and expanding Colorado's [[earned income tax credit]],<ref name=\"working\">{{cite news |first=Elizabeth |last=Aguilera |title=Working poor seek tax credit from state |url=http://www.denverpost.com/frontpage/ci_5655555  \n|work=Rocky Mountain News |date=April 13, 2007 |accessdate=2007-07-12 }}</ref> a move which met with resistance from legislative leaders in 2007 due to budget constraints.<ref name=\"reinstate\">{{cite news |first=Jason |last=Kosena |title=Kefalas seeks to reinstate tax credit |url=http://www.denverpost.com/frontpage/ci_5655555  \n|work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=June 14, 2007 |accessdate=2007-07-12 }}</ref> Kefalas introduced a bill in the 2008 session to restore Colorado's EITC at ten percent of the federal credit,<ref name=\"carbon\">{{cite news |first=Brian |last=Park |title=Carbon Conqueror  |url=http://www.rmchronicle.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=1757&Itemid=61\n|work=Rocky Mountain Chronicle |date=December 20, 2007 |accessdate=2007-12-20 }}</ref><ref name=\"briefs\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=Kefalas bill would restore tax credit |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080314/NEWS01/803140338/1002/CUSTOMERSERVICE02 |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=March 14, 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-03 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> but the bill was defeated in a House committee.<ref name=\"restore\">{{cite news |first=Perry |last=Swanson |title=Measure to restore state's Earned Income Tax Credit dies in committee |url=http://www.gazette.com/articles/credit_34879___article.html/state_families.html |work=Colorado Springs Gazette |date=April 2, 2008 |accessdate=2008-04-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724190627/http://www.gazette.com/articles/credit_34879___article.html/state_families.html |archivedate=July 24, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n===2008 election===\nHolding office in a closely contested district, Kefalas was expected to be targeted by Colorado Republicans during his 2008 re-election bid,<ref name=\"target\">{{cite news |first=Jason |last=Kosena |title=Kefalas a Republican target in 2008? |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070627/BLOGS02/70627010  \n|work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=June 27, 2007 |accessdate=2007-07-12 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> which he formally announced in January 2008.<ref name=\"reelect\">{{cite news |first=Jason |last=Kosena |title=Kefalas announces re-election bid |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080109/BLOGS02/80109027  \n|work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=January 9, 2008 |accessdate=2007-12-09 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Since taking office, Kefalas sought to maintain a dialogue with constituents by leading a series of monthly \"community conversations\" on topics ranging from health care to [[mobile home]] parks,<ref name=\"account8\"/><ref name=\"running\">{{cite web |url=http://squarestate.net/showDiary.do?diaryId=5066 |title=HD-52: John Kefalas running for re-election |accessdate=2008-01-09 |work=SquareState.net |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724081539/http://squarestate.net/showDiary.do?diaryId=5066 |archivedate=2011-07-24 }}</ref> and named sustainable economic development his top priority in office.<ref name=\"hopefuls\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=District 52 hopefuls respond |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20081019/NEWS03/810190330&s=d&page=2#pluckcomments |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=19 October 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-02 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nFormer Rep. [[Bob McCluskey]] announced his intention to run against Kefalas in February 2008, pitting the two against each other for the third time in as many election cycles<ref name=\"square\">{{cite news |first=Jason |last=Kosena |title=Kefalas, McCluskey to square off again in November |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080215/NEWS01/802150337/1002/CUSTOMERSERVICE02\n|work=Fort Collins COloradoan |date=February 15, 2008 |accessdate=2008-02-15 }}</ref> and creating a competitive race in what was seen as one of Colorado's \"swing\" districts.<ref name=\"mccl\">{{cite news |first=Jason |last=Kosena |title=HD 52: McCluskey looks to return to statehouse after see-saw races |url=http://coloradoindependent.com/14078/hd-52-mccluskey-looks-to-return-to-statehouse-after-see-saw-races |work=Colorado Independent |date=4 November 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-15 }}</ref>\n\nDuring the campaign, Kefalas held a fundraising advantage over McCluskey, with $60,000 cash on hand &mdash; three times as much as McCluskey &mdash; in mid-September.<ref name=\"cash\">{{cite news |first=Nate |last=Taylor |title=John Kefalas enjoys comfortable money lead over Bob McCluskey in HD 52 |url=http://coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080912/UPDATES01/80912007/1131/WINDSORBEACON01 |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=12 September 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-01 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> By late October, Kefalas had raised over $100,000, about $15,000 short of McCluskey's fundraising total;<ref name=\"exlaw\">{{cite news |first=David |last=Montero |title=Ex-lawmaker wants job back |url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/news/2008/oct/27/ex-lawmaker-wants-job-back/ |work=Rocky Mountain News |date=27 October 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-01 }}</ref> which included $65,000 that McCluskey donated to his own campaign.<ref name=\"buckle\">{{cite news |first=Nate |last=Taylor |title=Candidates buckle down |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20081030/NEWS03/810300324 |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=30 October 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-02 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nMcCluskey targeted Kefalas with a [[direct mail]] advertisement blaming Kefalas and the Democratic state legislature for high gasoline prices, a tactic Kefalas dismissed as \"negative campaigning.\"<ref name=\"gaspr\">{{cite news |first=Nate |last=Taylor |title=New ad targets Kefalas over gas prices |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20080927/NEWS03/809270331/1002/CUSTOMERSERVICE02 |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=27 September 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-01 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Kefalas also condemned independent ads attacking McCluskey's legislative record as having \"crossed the line of civility.\"<ref name=\"ad527\">{{cite news |first=Nate |last=Taylor |title=527 ads attack McCluskey |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20081022/UPDATES01/81022037/1002/NEWS01 |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=22 October 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-01 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> The [[527 group]] Accountability for Colorado also spent over $50,000 in support of Kefalas' re-election,<ref name=\"buckle\"/> including mailers attacking McCluskey's legislative record; Kefalas also expressed disapproval of these advertisements.<ref name=\"battlespec\">{{cite news |first=Trevor |last=Simonton |title=Kefalas, McCluskey battle special interests, negative advertisements |url=http://media.www.collegian.com/media/storage/paper864/news/2008/10/31/News/Kefalas.Mccluskey.Battle.Special.Interests.Negative.Advertisements-3518336.shtml |work=Rocky Mountain Collegian |date=31 October 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205072540/http://media.www.collegian.com/media/storage/paper864/news/2008/10/31/News/Kefalas.Mccluskey.Battle.Special.Interests.Negative.Advertisements-3518336.shtml |archivedate=5 December 2008 }}</ref>\n\nMcCluskey's bid to unseat Kefalas was endorsed by the ''[[Denver Post]]'',<ref name=\"dphouse\">{{cite news |author=Editorial Board |title=Post's picks in Colorado's House of Representatives |url=http://www.denverpost.com/headlines/ci_10741559 |work=Denver Post |date=17 October 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-01 }}\n</ref> while Kefalas was endorsed by the ''[[Windsor Beacon]]'' and the ''[[Fort Collins Coloradoan]]''.<ref name=\"csend\">{{cite news |first=Wendy |last=Norris |author2=Bob Spencer |title=State candidate endorsement watch |url=http://coloradoindependent.com/11911/state-candidate-endorsement-watch |work=Colorado Independent |date=3 November 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-07 }}</ref> Kefalas ultimately won a second term with about 59 percent of the popular vote,<ref name=\"bg52\">{{cite news |first=Jason |last=Kosena |title=Battleground HD 52 stays in Democratic hands |url=http://coloradoindependent.com/14403/battleground-hd-52-stays-in-democratic-hands |work=Colorado Independent |date=6 November 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-16 }}</ref><ref name=\"gen08\">{{cite web|url=http://coreports.ezvotetally.com/Reserved.ReportViewerWebControl.axd?ReportSession=jexpso55dlbays450fyzrmb4&ControlID=3a1b317069f040849b2b689d78addfc9&Culture=1033&UICulture=1033&ReportStack=1&OpType=ReportArea&Controller=dnn_ctr376_ViewRS2005_ReportViewer1&PageNumber=1&ZoomMode=Percent&ZoomPct=100&ReloadDocMap=true&SearchStartPage=0&LinkTarget=_top |title=Colorado Statewide Cumulative Report - 2008 General Election |accessdate=2008-12-04 |work=Colorado Secretary of State }}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> becoming the first Democrat to win re-election in the east Fort Collins district since 1936.<ref name=\"thankyous\">{{cite news |first=Rebecca |last=Boyle |title=It's Thank Yous All Around for FC Dems |url=http://www.fortcollinsnow.com/article/20081104/NEWS/811049962/1062&ParentProfile=1054&title=It's%20Thank%20Yous%20All%20Around%20for%20FC%20Dems |work=Fort Collins Now |date=4 November 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-16 }}</ref><ref name=\"successrare\">{{cite news |first=Nate |last=Taylor |title=Dem success rare in county |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/article/20081107/NEWS03/811070348/1002/CUSTOMERSERVICE02 |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=7 November 2008 |accessdate=2008-11-16 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\n===2009 legislative session===\n{{Infobox Colorado Legislation\n|Title=Rep.\n|Name=Kefalas\n|Year=2009\n|Bill Number 1=HB09-1064\n|Bill Number 2=HB09-1105\n|Bill Number 3=HB09-1134\n|Bill Number 4=HB09-1251\n|Bill Number 5=HB09-1273\n|Bill Link 1=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2009a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/F05E81CDDCB2622587257537001A2A51?Open&file=1064_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 2=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2009a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/5F10F2ACE5B377238725753C007B97C1?Open&file=1105_enr.pdf\n|Bill Link 3=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2009a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/CBD8440EA56F25038725753900757E9E?Open&file=1134_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 4=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2009a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/C20BC9AA013B97C38725753C00709A97?Open&file=1251_01.pdf\n|Bill Link 5=http://www.leg.state.co.us/clics/clics2009a/csl.nsf/fsbillcont/E5CFE643118E61458725754A007B14D2?Open&file=1273_eng.pdf\n|Bill Title 1=Concerning [...] establishing the Economic Opportunity Poverty Reduction Task Force for the purpose of advancing economic opportunity while reducing child and family poverty.\n|Bill Title 2=Concerning the creation of the Colorado Innovation Investment Tax Credit [...]\n|Bill Title 3=Concerning the Colorado Railroad Authority, and [...] creating the authority for the purpose of planning, designing, developing, financing, constructing, operating, and maintaining a passenger rail system [...]\n|Bill Title 4=Concerning the disclosure of criminal justice records.\n|Bill Title 5=Concerning the creation of a health care authority that shall be the administrator for health care services in Colorado.\n|Bill Status 1=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 2=Signed by Gov. [[Bill Ritter (politician)|Ritter]]\n|Bill Status 3=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 4=Postponed indefinitely in House committee\n|Bill Status 5=Laid over on third reading in House\n}}\n\nFor the 2009 legislative session, Kefalas was named to seats on the House Appropriations Committee, the House Finance Committee, and the House Health and Human Services Committee.<ref name=\"cmte09\">{{cite press release|title=House Democrats Unveil 2009 Committee Chairs & Assignments |date=18 November 2008 |publisher=Colorado House Democrats |url=http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2008/11/house-democrats-unveil-2009-committee-chairs-assignments.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103101139/http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2008/11/house-democrats-unveil-2009-committee-chairs-assignments.html |archivedate= 3 January 2010 }}</ref> Kefalas has named health care reform as his top priority and planned on introducing legislation to create a [[single-payer universal health care]] system in Colorado during the 2009 session.<ref name=\"advancek\">{{cite news |first=Pat |last=Ferrier |title=Kefalas to advance statewide insurance |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/article/20081206/BUSINESS/812060319 |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=6 December 2008 |accessdate=2008-12-06 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref name=\"comprehen\">{{cite news |author=Staff Reports |title=Kefalas readies comprehensive health-care bill |url=http://www.ncbr.com/article.asp?id=97568 |work=Northern Colorado Business Report |date=9 December 2008 |accessdate=2008-12-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714161811/http://www.ncbr.com/article.asp?id=97568 |archive-date=14 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The bill was introduced as a proposal to create a 23-member commission to make recommendations as to how to implement a single-payer system, and was reported favorably out of a House committee.<ref name=\"revamp\">{{cite news |first=Bob |last=Mook\n|title=Bill to revamp Colorado health care system advances |url=http://denver.bizjournals.com/denver/stories/2009/03/16/daily46.html |work=Denver Business Journal |date=18 March 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-24}}\n</ref><ref name=\"canadian\">{{cite news |first=Tim |last=Hoover\n|title=Bill backing Canadian-type health plan gains in Colo. House |url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_11945054 |work=Denver Post |date=19 March 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-24}}</ref> However, Kefalas was one vote short of the 33 necessary to pass the legislation out of the house, and in April, asked that the legislation be killed.<ref name=\"fails\">{{cite news |first=Joe |last=Hanel |title=State single-payer health-care effort fails |url=http://durangoherald.com/sections/News/2009/04/16/State_singlepayer_healthcare_effort_fails/ |work=Durango Herald |date=16 April 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090419214654/http://durangoherald.com/sections/News/2009/04/16/State%5Fsinglepayer%5Fhealthcare%5Feffort%5Ffails/ |archive-date=2009-04-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nKefalas also sponsored the Colorado Innovation Investment Tax Credit,<ref name=\"transform\">{{cite news |first=Kristen |last=Tatti |title=2009 was 'transformational' year for RMI2 |url=http://ncbr.com/article.asp?id=103470 |work=Northern Colorado Business Report |date=18 December 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102140406/http://ncbr.com/article.asp?id=103470 |archive-date=2 January 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> legislation to create $750,000 in tax credits for [[angel investor]]s in startup companies,<ref name=\"lowbudget\">{{cite news |first=Bob |last=Mook |title='Low-budget' ideas given to legislators |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/denver/stories/2008/12/08/daily17.html |work=Denver Business Journal |date=8 December 2008 |accessdate=2008-12-25 }}</ref><ref name=\"inside2\">{{cite news |first=Rebecca |last=Boyle\n|title=Inside Politics (Part 2): Activists Color Their Legislative Agenda |url=http://www.fortcollinsnow.com/article/20090204/NEWS/902049983/1026/NONE&title=Inside%20Politics%20(Part%202):%20%20Activists%20Color%20Their%20Legislative%20Agenda |work=Fort Collins Now |date=4 December 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-24}}</ref><ref name=\"angels\">{{cite news |first=Ed |last=Sealover\n|title=New Colorado laws benefit tech investors, boost energy loans \n|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/denver/stories/2009/08/31/daily45.html |work=Denver Business Journal |date=1 September 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-24}}</ref> to increase support for [[job training]] programs,<ref name=\"coalitionforce\">{{cite news |first=Pat |last=Ferrier |title=Northern Colorado coalition pitches work force initiative |url=http://www.coloradoan.com/article/20081223/BUSINESS/812230321/1046 |work=Fort Collins Coloradoan |date=23 December 2008 |accessdate=2008-12-26 }} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> and to create a Colorado Railroad Authority to begin planning for statewide [[passenger rail]] service.<ref name=\"passrail\">{{cite news |first=Charles |last=Ashby |title=Passenger rail service bills on track |url=http://www.chieftain.com/articles/2009/01/25/news/denver_bureau/doc497c08c320ec7020554294.txt |work=Pueblo Chieftain |date=25 January 2009 |accessdate=2009-02-22 }}</ref>\n\nKefalas also sponsored legislation to create an Economic Opportunity/Poverty Reduction Task Force,<ref name=\"milrem\">{{cite news\n |first=Kathryn \n |last=Dailey \n |title=Bill regarding military remains now in state Senate \n |url=http://www.reporterherald.com/news_story.asp?ID=21320 \n |work=Loveland Reporter-Herald \n |date=2 February 2009 \n |accessdate=2009-07-03 \n}}{{dead link|date=January 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"agendas\">{{cite news |first=Terrance |last=Carroll\n|title=Capitol Agendas |url=http://www.chieftain.com/articles/2009/03/15/editorial/doc49bc683ee3ac6255989846.txt |work=Pueblo Chieftain |date=15 March 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-24}}\n</ref> which he chaired following the regular session.<ref>{{cite news |first=Tina |last=Griego |title=Griego: Panel's hard knocks may open doors |url=http://www.denverpost.com/news/ci_13164705 |work=Denver Post |date=20 August 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-26}}</ref> The committee's objective is to develop plans to reduce Colorado's poverty rate by half in ten years, examining a broad range of issues from economic development to education to transportation to tax policy,<ref name=\"reduce\">{{cite news |author=Staff Report |title=Colo. task force looks for ways to reduce poverty |url=http://www.summitdaily.com/article/20090727/NEWS/907279979/1078&ParentProfile=1055 |work=Summit Daily News |date=27 July 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224015513/http://www.summitdaily.com/article/20090727/NEWS/907279979/1078%26ParentProfile%3D1055 |archive-date=24 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and it considered potential legislation on topics ranging from the [[earned income tax credit]] to [[rent control]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Stephen K. |last=Paulson |title=Colo. lawmakers consider measures to cut poverty |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/businesstechnology/2010100970_apusreducingpovertycolorado.html |work=Seattle Times |date=20 October 2009 |accessdate=2010-01-04}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the legislation session, Kefalas was the only male legislator honored with the Colorado Lawmakers Award by the Denver Women\u2019s Commission and the Colorado Women\u2019s Chamber of Commerce.<ref name=\"menwomen\">{{cite press release |title=Rep. John Kefalas, A Man Among Women! |date=3 November 2009 |publisher=Colorado House Democrats |url=http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2009/11/rep-john-kefalas-a-man-among-women.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091110163127/http://cohousedems.typepad.com/my_weblog/2009/11/rep-john-kefalas-a-man-among-women.html |archivedate=10 November 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===2010 election===\nIn August 2009, Kefalas announced his intention to seek a third term in the legislature in the November 2010 legislative elections.<ref name=\"frontra\">{{cite news |author=Staff Report |title=Front Range Briefs |url=http://www.reporterherald.com/news_story.asp?id=24556 |work=Loveland Reporter Herald |date=23 August 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-24 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  Kefalas was reelected with 57% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|title=CBS Election Results|url=http://elections.cbslocal.com/cbs/kcnc/20101102/race85.shtml|work=CBS Election Results|accessdate=11 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2012 election===\nRepresentative Kefalas announced that he would seek election to the [[Colorado Senate|state senate]] seat vacated by [[Bob Bacon]].  Kefalas' bid was endorsed by The [[Fort Collins Coloradoan]] and several former elected officials.<ref>{{cite web|title=John Kefalas - Endorsements|url=http://www.johnkefalas.org/endorsements|access-date=2012-11-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102212320/http://www.johnkefalas.org/endorsements|archive-date=2012-11-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>  In the [[United States elections, 2012|2012 General Election]], Representative Kefalas faced Republican challenger [[Syndi Anderson]] for the open Senate seat.  Kefalas was elected by a wide margin of 58% to 36% with the remainder of the vote going to third-party candidates.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://results.enr.clarityelections.com/CO/43032/111283/en/summary.html# |title=CO - Election Results - Colorado Secretary of State |access-date=2012-11-11 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314203900/http://results.enr.clarityelections.com/CO/43032/111283/en/summary.html |archive-date=2017-03-14 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://data.denverpost.com/election/results/state-house/2012/ |title=State House 2012 Election Results - Denver Post}}</ref>  Senator Kefalas now represents the people of State Senate District 14.\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://leg.colorado.gov/legislators/john-kefalas John Kefalas profile, Colorado General Assembly]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20171202105134/http://www.johnkefalas.org/ State Rep. John Kefalas]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071009002444/http://www.kefalas2008.com/ John Kefalas 2008 campaign]\n* [https://www.myspace.com/johnkefalas John Kefalas MySpace page]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kefalas, John}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Greek emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Fairleigh Dickinson University alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the Colorado House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Fort Collins, Colorado]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Colorado state senators]]\n[[Category:County commissioners in Colorado]]\n", "name_user": "Blizzardwind", "label": "safe", "comment": "added senate district links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Kefalas"}
{"title_page": "Little Boy (song)", "text_new": "{{short description|2017 single by KSI}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Little Boy\n| cover      = \n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[KSI (entertainer)|KSI]]\n| album      =\n| EP         = Disstracktions\n| released   = 13 August 2017\n| format     =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| recorded   = August 2017\n| studio     = [[Los Angeles]]\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Hip hop]]\n| length     = 2:10\n| label      = [[Island Records|Island]]{{efn|group=upper-alpha|\"Little Boy\" was originally released independently onto YouTube, but has been licensed to [[Island Records]] since 29 September 2017 due to the song's appearance on KSI's fourth extended play Disstracktions.}}\n| writer     = [[KSI (entertainer)|Olajide Olatunji]]<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web |title=Little Boy by KSI |url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/79079729/credits |website=Tidal |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n| producer   = Zeeshan<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n| chronology = [[KSI (entertainer)|KSI]]\n| prev_title = Earthquake\n| prev_year  = 2017\n| next_title = Two Birds, One Stone\n| next_year  = 2017\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|YQKEJyDiIZc|\"Little Boy\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Little Boy'''\" is a song by British YouTube personality and rapper [[KSI (entertainer)|KSI]]. The song is a [[Diss (music)|diss track]] aimed at YouTuber and fellow [[Sidemen]] member Wroetoshaw in response to Wroetoshaw's diss track \"KSI Sucks\". The song is produced by British producer Zeeshan. It was released onto YouTube on 13 August 2017, five days after Wroetoshaw released \"KSI Sucks\", and more than a month later, on 29 September 2017, the song was made available for digital download and streaming on all platforms through [[Island Records]] due to its appearance on KSI's fourth extended play ''Disstracktions''. The song charted at number 82 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] after the release of ''Disstracktions.''<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/48106/ksi/|title=KSI {{!}} full Official Chart History {{!}} Official Charts Company|website=www.officialcharts.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nOn 4 August 2017, while on vacation in [[Los Angeles]], KSI announced via [[Twitter]] that he would be leaving the British YouTube group [[Sidemen]]. He tweeted: \"Yeah, I think it's time I move on from the sidemen. The journey has been A LOT of fun, but it's time to move on to bigger things\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ksiolajidebt/status/893339490105794560?lang=en|title=Yeah, I think it's time I move on from the sidemen. The journey has been A LOT of fun, but it's time to move on to bigger things.|last=KSI|date=2017-08-03|website=@ksiolajidebt|language=en|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref> On 6 August, KSI uploaded a video to his YouTube channel titled \"I'm Leaving The Sidemen\" where he further explained his decision to leave the group. At the start of the video, he cited a fall-out with fellow Sidemen member Ethan Payne (known online as Behzinga) as the reason for him leaving the group, and throughout the video, he continually makes jibes at Payne as well as the rest of the Sidemen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0zeg_RDsn-4|title=I'm Leaving The Sidemen|last=|first=|date=6 August 2017|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dexerto.com/news/ksi-explains-reasons-behind-leaving-sidemen-reveals-new-room-banks-house/33738/p7|title=KSI Explains Reasons Behind Leaving The Sidemen And Reveals New Room At Faze Banks' House|last=|first=|date=7 August 2017|work=Dexerto|access-date=7 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhile Payne responded to this by making a diss track against KSI<ref>{{Citation|title=Behzinga - Drama (Official Music Video)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ki1sl4Ad08Q|language=en|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/youtuber-drama-behzinga-sends-ksi|title=There's YouTuber \"Drama\" as Behzinga Sends for KSI|last=|first=|date=8 August 2017|website=GRM Daily|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>, fellow Sidemen member Harry Lewis (known online as Wroetoshaw) decided to also respond with a diss track against KSI. The diss track, titled \"KSI Sucks\", was released onto YouTube on 8 August.<ref>{{Citation|title=W2S - KSI Sucks (RiceGum & KSI Diss Track) Official Video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pmcfL_qLhMo|language=en|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref> After responding to Payne with his own diss track titled \"Earthquake\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uO0ZNHZ5F1E|title=KSI ft Ricegum - Earthquake (Official Music Video)|last=|first=|date=12 August 2017|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>, KSI released the diss track \"Little Boy\" in response to Wroetoshaw on 13 August.\n\n== Promotion ==\nA thirty seconds-long teaser for \"Little Boy\" was included at the end of KSI's diss track on Payne, \"Earthquake\", which was released on 12 August, one day before the release of \"Little Boy\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Commercial performance ==\nThe song entered the UK Singles Chart at number 82 due to its appearance on KSI's fourth extended play, ''Disstracktions'', before dropping out of the top 100 in the next week.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/20171006/7501/|title=Official Singles Chart Top 100 {{!}} Official Charts Company|website=www.officialcharts.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Music video ==\nThe music video, directed by Jovan Thomas, was filmed at the mansion of American YouTubers [[RiceGum]], [[FaZe Banks]] and Alissa Violet in Los Angeles in August 2017 and was uploaded to KSI's YouTube channel on 13 August 2017. As of April 2020, it has 56 million views.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YQKEJyDiIZc|title=KSI - Little Boy (Official Music Video)|last=|first=|date=13 August 2017|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Response ==\nOn 19 August 2017, six days after KSI released \"Little Boy\", Wroetoshaw uploaded a response diss track titled \"KSI Exposed\" to his YouTube channel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w-VuZzsZq0c|title=W2S - KSI Exposed (Official Music Video)|last=|first=|date=19 August 2017|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> As of April 2020, it has 14 million views.\n\n== Credits and personnel ==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n{{div col}}\n*[[KSI (entertainer)|KSI]] \u2013 vocals, songwriter\n*Zeeshan \u2013 producer\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Charts ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2017)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Scotland|87|date=20171006|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UK|82|date=20171006|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UKrandb|39|date=20171006|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 April 2020}}\n|}\n\n== Release history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n! scope=\"col\" |Region\n! scope=\"col\" |Date\n! scope=\"col\" |Format\n! scope=\"col\" |Label\n! scope=\"col\" |Ref.\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"row\" |Various\n| 13 August 2017\n| [[Streaming media|Streaming]] ([[YouTube]])\n| [[Self-publishing|Self-released]]\n| <ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n| 29 September 2017\n| {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| [[Island Records|Island{{efn|group=upper-alpha|\"Little Boy\" was originally released independently onto YouTube, but has been licensed to [[Island Records]] since 29 September 2017 due to the song's appearance on KSI's fourth extended play Disstracktions.|name=}}]][[Little Boy (song)#cite%20note-17|<span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[upper-alpha 2]</span>]][[Little Boy (song)#cite%20note-13|<span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[upper-alpha 2]</span>]]\n| <ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/little-boy/1440882143|title=Disstracktions - EP by KSI|last=|first=|date=29 September 2017|website=iTunes|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Notes ==\n<references group=\"upper-alpha\" responsive=\"1\"></references>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YQKEJyDiIZc Music video] on [[YouTube]]\n* [https://genius.com/Ksi-little-boy-lyrics Lyrics of the song] at [[Genius (website)|Genius]]\n\n{{KSI}}\n[[Category:2017 songs]]\n[[Category:2017 singles]]\n[[Category:Diss tracks]]\n[[Category:Island Records singles]]\n[[Category:KSI (entertainer) songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by KSI]]\n[[Category:YouTube music videos]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2017 single by KSI}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Little Boy\n| cover      = \n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[KSI (entertainer)|KSI]]\n| album      =\n| EP         = Disstracktions\n| released   = 13 August 2017\n| format     =\n* [[Music download|Digital download]]\n* [[Streaming media|streaming]]\n| recorded   = August 2017\n| studio     = [[Los Angeles]]\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Hip hop]]\n| length     = 2:10\n| label      = [[Island Records|Island]]{{efn|group=upper-alpha|\"Little Boy\" was originally released independently onto YouTube, but has been licensed to [[Island Records]] since 29 September 2017 due to the song's appearance on KSI's fourth extended play Disstracktions.}}\n| writer     = [[KSI (entertainer)|Olajide Olatunji]]<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web |title=Little Boy by KSI |url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/79079729/credits |website=Tidal |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n| producer   = Zeeshan<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n| chronology = [[KSI (entertainer)|KSI]]\n| prev_title = Earthquake\n| prev_year  = 2017\n| next_title = Two Birds, One Stone\n| next_year  = 2017\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|YQKEJyDiIZc|\"Little Boy\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Little Boy'''\" is a song by British YouTube personality and rapper [[KSI (entertainer)|KSI]]. The song is a [[Diss (music)|diss track]] aimed at YouTuber and fellow [[Sidemen]] member Wroetoshaw in response to Wroetoshaw's diss track \"KSI Sucks\". The song is produced by British producer Zeeshan. It was released onto YouTube on 13 August 2017, five days after Wroetoshaw released \"KSI Sucks\", and more than a month later, on 29 September 2017, the song was made available for digital download and streaming on all platforms through [[Island Records]] due to its appearance on KSI's fourth extended play ''Disstracktions''. The song charted at number 82 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] after the release of ''Disstracktions.''<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/48106/ksi/|title=KSI {{!}} full Official Chart History {{!}} Official Charts Company|website=www.officialcharts.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nOn 4 August 2017, while on vacation in [[Los Angeles]], KSI announced via [[Twitter]] that he would be leaving the British YouTube group [[Sidemen]]. He tweeted: \"Yeah, I think it's time I move on from the sidemen. The journey has been A LOT of fun, but it's time to move on to bigger things\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ksiolajidebt/status/893339490105794560?lang=en|title=Yeah, I think it's time I move on from the sidemen. The journey has been A LOT of fun, but it's time to move on to bigger things.|last=KSI|date=2017-08-03|website=@ksiolajidebt|language=en|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref> On 6 August, KSI uploaded a video to his YouTube channel titled \"I'm Leaving The Sidemen\" where he further explained his decision to leave the group. At the start of the video, he cited a fall-out with fellow Sidemen member Ethan Payne (known online as Behzinga) as the reason for him leaving the group, and throughout the video, he continually makes jibes at Payne as well as the rest of the Sidemen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0zeg_RDsn-4|title=I'm Leaving The Sidemen|last=|first=|date=6 August 2017|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dexerto.com/news/ksi-explains-reasons-behind-leaving-sidemen-reveals-new-room-banks-house/33738/p7|title=KSI Explains Reasons Behind Leaving The Sidemen And Reveals New Room At Faze Banks' House|last=|first=|date=7 August 2017|work=Dexerto|access-date=7 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhile Payne responded to this by making a diss track against KSI<ref>{{Citation|title=Behzinga - Drama (Official Music Video)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ki1sl4Ad08Q|language=en|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://grmdaily.com/video/youtuber-drama-behzinga-sends-ksi|title=There's YouTuber \"Drama\" as Behzinga Sends for KSI|last=|first=|date=8 August 2017|website=GRM Daily|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>, fellow Sidemen member Harry Lewis (known online as Wroetoshaw) decided to also respond with a diss track against KSI. The diss track, titled \"KSI Sucks\", was released onto YouTube on 8 August.<ref>{{Citation|title=W2S - KSI Sucks (RiceGum & KSI Diss Track) Official Video|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pmcfL_qLhMo|language=en|access-date=2020-01-21}}</ref> After responding to Payne with his own diss track titled \"Earthquake\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uO0ZNHZ5F1E|title=KSI ft Ricegum - Earthquake (Official Music Video)|last=|first=|date=12 August 2017|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>, KSI released the diss track \"Little Boy\" in response to Wroetoshaw on 13 August.\n\n== Promotion ==\nA thirty seconds-long teaser for \"Little Boy\" was included at the end of KSI's diss track on Payne, \"Earthquake\", which was released on 12 August, one day before the release of \"Little Boy\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Commercial performance ==\nThe song entered the UK Singles Chart at number 82 due to its appearance on KSI's fourth extended play, ''Disstracktions'', before dropping out of the top 100 in the next week.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/20171006/7501/|title=Official Singles Chart Top 100 {{!}} Official Charts Company|website=www.officialcharts.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Music video ==\nThe music video, directed by Jovan Thomas, was filmed at the mansion of American YouTubers [[RiceGum]], [[FaZe Banks]] and Alissa Violet in Los Angeles in August 2017 and was uploaded to KSI's YouTube channel on 13 August 2017. As of April 2020, it has 56 million views.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YQKEJyDiIZc|title=KSI - Little Boy (Official Music Video)|last=|first=|date=13 August 2017|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Response ==\nOn 19 August 2017, six days after KSI released \"Little Boy\", Wroetoshaw uploaded a response diss track titled \"KSI Exposed\" to his YouTube channel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w-VuZzsZq0c|title=W2S - KSI Exposed (Official Music Video)|last=|first=|date=19 August 2017|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 April 2020}}</ref> As of April 2020, it has 14 million views.\n\n== Credits and personnel ==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n{{div col}}\n*[[KSI (entertainer)|KSI]] \u2013 vocals, songwriter\n*Zeeshan \u2013 producer\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Charts ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2017)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Scotland|87|date=20171006|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UK|82|date=20171006|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UKrandb|39|date=20171006|rowheader=true|accessdate=20 April 2020}}\n|}\n\n== Release history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n! scope=\"col\" |Region\n! scope=\"col\" |Date\n! scope=\"col\" |Format\n! scope=\"col\" |Label\n! scope=\"col\" |Ref.\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"row\" |Various\n| 13 August 2017\n| [[Streaming media|Streaming]] ([[YouTube]])\n| [[Self-publishing|Self-released]]\n| <ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n| 29 September 2017\n| {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| [[Island Records|Island{{efn|group=upper-alpha|\"Little Boy\" was originally released independently onto YouTube, but has been licensed to [[Island Records]] since 29 September 2017 due to the song's appearance on KSI's fourth extended play Disstracktions.|name=}}]][[Little Boy (song)#cite%20note-13|<span class=\"mw-reflink-text\">[upper-alpha 2]</span>]]\n| <ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/little-boy/1440882143|title=Disstracktions - EP by KSI|last=|first=|date=29 September 2017|website=iTunes|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Notes ==\n<references group=\"upper-alpha\" responsive=\"1\"></references>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YQKEJyDiIZc Music video] on [[YouTube]]\n* [https://genius.com/Ksi-little-boy-lyrics Lyrics of the song